<paragraph blockId="77.[264,1322,1084,1190]" box="[264,389,1084,1109]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis box="[264,389,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[264,1322,1084,1190]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
Named after the 
<typeStatus box="[510,560,1124,1150]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">type</typeStatus>
locality river, but based on an older spelling, Adson, rather than the modern spelling, Adsone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[264,714,1244,1310]" box="[264,714,1244,1310]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis box="[264,407,1244,1269]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Distribution</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[312,455,1284,1310]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">VANUATU</collectingCountry>
: Santo, Adsone River.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[264,1323,1364,1870]" box="[264,387,1364,1389]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis box="[264,387,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[264,1323,1364,1870]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[312,562,1404,1429]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis box="[312,562,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Simulium adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in Santo only, along with small numbers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="steatopygium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">S. steatopygium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae. Association of larvae and pupae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[946,1099,1444,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis box="[946,1099,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">S. adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confirmed by comparison of pupal cuticle (
<figureCitation box="[615,697,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="24.[264,367,1403,1427]" captionTargetBox="[265,1323,326,1379]" captionTargetId="figure-103@24.[264,1323,326,1379]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 8. Hebridosimulium. Pupal thoracic cuticle. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071411" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071411/files/figure.png" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Fig. 8f</figureCitation>
) and gills (
<figureCitation box="[836,936,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[264,367,1531,1555]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,326,1507]" captionTargetId="figure-95@27.[264,1323,326,1507]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pupal gill filaments of Hebridosimulium species (continued). Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071415" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071415/files/figure.png" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Fig. 10e</figureCitation>
) of pharate pupae in the mature last-instar larvae, to the mature pupae. The 
<typeStatus box="[788,838,1524,1550]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation box="[954,1055,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="83.[264,367,1634,1658]" captionTargetBox="[301,1278,310,1610]" captionTargetId="figure-141@83.[301,1279,310,1610]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURE 24. Habitats of larvae of Hebridosimulium species. a–e. Vanuatu.a. Santo, Adsone River. Type locality of S. adsonense. b. Santo, upper cascade, tributary of Sarakata River. Type locality of S. paradisium. c. Efate, Mele Cascade. Type locality of S. steatopygium. Note travertine terraces. d. South Pentecost, Warbot River. Type locality of S. supercilium. e. Santo, small stream, Millennium Cave region. Typical locality of S. subparadisium. f–i. Fiji. Habitats of S. laciniatum larvae. f. Viti Levu, Abaca Village, above Vereni Falls. Type region. g. Taveuni, Wairiki, Devo Peak, looking down water slide. h. Kadavu, Kadavacoro Village, Wailea Waterfall. i. Vanu Levu, Waisala Rain Forest Reserve, Ravini River." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071449/files/figure.png" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Fig. 24a</figureCitation>
) is shallow, with very fast water (respectively ca. 
<quantity box="[595,656,1564,1590]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[718,789,1564,1590]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" unit="m" value="1.8">1.8 m</quantity>
/s) on an old concrete causeway. Larvae and pupae were also recovered from a riffle upstream. Larvae exhibit behaviours similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rubtsov" authorityYear="1974" box="[375,505,1644,1669]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Inseliellum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[375,505,1644,1669]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Inseliellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Polynesia that are adapted to shallow fast water (
<bibRefCitation author="Craig, D. A." box="[1167,1309,1644,1670]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" pagination="855 - 904" refId="ref41323" refString="Craig, D. A. (1997) A taxonomic revision of the Pacific black fly subgenus Inseliellum (Diptera: Simuliidae). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 75, 855 - 904." type="journal article" year="1997">Craig 1997</bibRefCitation>
), namely, even spacing of larvae and lack of body twisting, so that the ventral surface of the labral fans are directed towards the substrate. The latter behaviour is similar to that observed for larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[532,695,1764,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradisium">
<emphasis box="[532,695,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">S. paradisium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The number of hooks on the posterior circlet is also higher, again in keeping with adaptation to high-velocity habitats.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="77.[264,1323,1364,1870]" lastBlockId="78.[264,1323,284,390]" lastPageId="78" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
With the larva not markedly steatopygous and the pupal cuticle unique, placement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[264,418,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis box="[264,418,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">S. adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[506,662,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="steatopygium">
<emphasis box="[506,662,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">steatopygium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group was based solely on the genitalia of the single female adult. The relationship of this species may have to be reconsidered once additional material comes to hand.
</paragraph>
